text:
After six seasons, Miami’s Raul Esparza has left NBC’s “Law & Order: Special Victims Unit” where he played assistant district attorney Rafael Barba.

During Wednesday night’s episode, Barba found himself as the defendant after committing a mercy killing or what he called “a justified homicide” of a brain dead toddler. Although the character (spoiler alert) was found not guilty, he decided to leave his job as an ADA.

In a Tweet to the show’s fans and his co-star Mariska Hargitay, Esparza wrote, “Goodbye Barba. Thank you. You changed my life. My squad. And you, you always, my Liv, my friend Mariska. I will always treasure my time with all of you.”

Barba was a popular character on the long-running procedural where he was a by-the-book, no-nonsense attorney. In the role, Esparza, who is Cuban-American, also used his Spanish in some scenes. Many of his scenes were with Hargitay discussing the details of a case in his office and in court. Wednesday night, the hashtag barbaontrial was trending about the episode as fans and cast members were sad about the actor’s departure from the show.

What’s next for Esparza, who graduated from Belen Jesuit Prepatory School in Miami in 1988?

After playing the same role on NBC, he’s returning to his theatre roots for a “Chess” revival at the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts in Washington D.C., according to Entertainment Weekly.

“I’m a theater guy, so it’s like having a script in front of you that keeps changing every time you go to do it,” said Esparza, who has had roles in the 2000 “The Rocky Horror Show” revival on Broadway as well as “Cabaret,” “Taboo,” “Chitty Chitty Bang Bang” and “Company.”

“The learning process of how roles grow over a period of time with a series has been kind of fascinating, and I just felt I had reached the end of what I wanted to explore where they were writing.”

Esparza’s departure from “Law and Order: SVU” followed that of another Miami native, Danny Pino, who played detective Nick Amaro from 2011 to 2015.

The Miami Coral Park Senior High graduate and Florida International University alumnus is joining the “Sons of Anarchy’’ spinoff called “Mayans MC” on the FX network.

